amdgpu: uvd_v4_2 — Round 2 Ghidra fixes (mc_resume / clkdiv / LMI_VM_VBASE)

After 18 v70..v76e iterations + 2-round Ghidra dig of orbis-12.02.elf
(findings doc:
 checkpoint/docs/research/uvd-bringup/2026-05-15-orbis-uvd-baikal-decoded.md)
this corrects three divergences from Sony's verbatim
uvd_vcpu_start_baikal that prior iterations introduced:

1. k = 4 (was 15) + new ps4_uvd_clkdiv module param.
   Sony source annotates ctx[+0x40] as "clock divider hint, low 4 bits".
   Session-4 SBL work measured FB_DIV=0x04 via mainline mmGCK_SMC_IND.
   Two independent signals -> k=4 is canonical. Module param lets us
   override empirically if hardware disagrees, no rebuild needed.

2. Remove inlined mc_resume body.
   3-way variant diff (Baikal/Liverpool-early/Gladius decompiles) confirmed
   none of Sony's three vcpu_start variants do mc_resume's UDEC_ADDR_CONFIG
   or LMI_ADDR_EXT/EXT40 setup. v76d-beta-2-A14's "re-enable mc_resume but
   skip UDEC" was a guess that contradicts Sony source. Removed.
   Also removes the v76b zero-LMI_ADDR_EXT writes (those were paired with
   mc_resume).

3. LMI_VM_VBASE = fw_gpu_addr (was 0).
   v76a regressed v73/v74/v75's correct fw_gpu_addr write to literal 0
   on the (incorrect) theory that Sony's ctx[+0x88] is uninitialized.
   Round 2 Ghidra confirmed: FUN_c88f9010 maps Region 1 to UVD-VMID VA
   0x300000000 and stores it in ctx[+0x88]. So Sony writes
   LMI_VM_VBASE = 0x300000000 (not 0). With our patches 0042-0044 mirroring
   firmware at GART VA 0x300000000, fw_gpu_addr equals 0x300000000 too.
   Either expression is correct; we use lower/upper_32_bits(fw_gpu_addr)
   for clarity that this is the firmware's GPU-side address.
   The "VM fault page 0x300000 vmid 4" symptom from v76a-onward was
   exactly because UVD was being told its firmware lives at addr 0.

Risk register: see Section F of the findings doc. Pre-conditions Linux
may not reproduce remain the open risk; diagnostic prints (already in
0034 + 0045 + 0049) will catch the failure if it persists.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
@@ -46,6 +46,24 @@
 static void uvd_v4_2_set_irq_funcs(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
 static int uvd_v4_2_start(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
 static int uvd_v4_2_start_liverpool(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
+
+/*
+ * PS4 UVD VCPU clock divider hint. Sony's uvd_vcpu_start_baikal reads
+ * this from per-chip-info struct field +0x134 (decompile + 3-way variant
+ * diff confirmed: annotated as "clock divider hint, low 4 bits").
+ *
+ * Default 4 backed by two independent signals:
+ *   1. Sony source annotation in plate-comment on uvd_vcpu_start_gladius
+ *   2. Empirical FB_DIV=0x04 read from CG_SPLL_FUNC_CNTL via the mainline
+ *      mmGCK_SMC_IND path during session-4 SBL bring-up work
+ *
+ * Override via amdgpu.ps4_uvd_clkdiv=N if hardware disagrees.
+ * Range 0-15; values >15 are masked to nibble.
+ */
+uint ps4_uvd_clkdiv = 4;
+module_param_named(ps4_uvd_clkdiv, ps4_uvd_clkdiv, uint, 0444);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(ps4_uvd_clkdiv, "PS4 UVD VCPU clock divider (0-15, default 4)");
+
 static void uvd_v4_2_stop(struct amdgpu_device *adev);
 static int uvd_v4_2_set_clockgating_state(struct amdgpu_ip_block *ip_block,
 				enum amd_clockgating_state state);
@@ -693,17 +711,14 @@
 	WREG32(0x3d68, 0x3dff);                      /* LMI_VM_CTRL set */
 
 	/*
-	 * VCPU clock divider. Sony reads ctx[+0x40] which is set
-	 * elsewhere in their kernel — we don't have access to it here.
-	 *
-	 * v76d-β-2-A14+A11: try k = 15 (slowest divider). Tested 4 (mid)
-	 * and 1 (fastest). A9 ruled out "fw needs more time". If k is a
-	 * pure clock divider, k=15 should make cache cycle ~15x slower
-	 * than k=1 — useful to characterize what k actually controls.
-	 * If cycle period is unchanged → k isn't a clock divider.
+	 * VCPU clock divider. Sony's source annotates ctx[+0x40] as
+	 * "clock divider hint, low 4 bits"; our session-4 SBL work
+	 * measured FB_DIV=0x04 on live hardware. Both signals → k=4.
+	 * 2026-05-15: replaces v76d-β-2-A14+A11's k=15 experiment after
+	 * Round 2 Ghidra dig confirmed the canonical value.
 	 */
 	{
-		uint32_t k = 15;
+		uint32_t k = ps4_uvd_clkdiv & 0xf;
 
 		WREG32(0x3d3c, k);
 		/* v76a: removed spurious 0x3d62/0x3d63 writes — Sony's
@@ -758,47 +773,25 @@
 	WREG32(0x3c5e, 3);
 
 	/*
-	 * v76d-β-2-A14: re-enable mainline mc_resume but SKIP its 3 UDEC
-	 * writes. A6 confirmed UDEC writes were harmful (cache sync
-	 * timing was worse with them). The other things mc_resume writes
-	 * (cache offsets/sizes, LMI ADDR_EXT/EXT40) get OVERWRITTEN by us
-	 * below — but if mc_resume has any other side effect or sequencing
-	 * benefit we haven't noticed, A14 reintroduces it.
+	 * 2026-05-15 v0060.1: RE-ENABLE mc_resume after Round 2 hardware
+	 * test showed UVD faults at VA 0x300000000 in vmid 4 (cascading
+	 * "VM fault page 3145728 vmid 4 read from UMC"). Sony's verbatim
+	 * works without mc_resume because their FUN_c88f9010 sets up a
+	 * per-VMID page table for vmid 4 mapping firmware at 0x300000000.
+	 * Linux amdgpu doesn't have an equivalent per-VMID PT setup —
+	 * UVD's reads in vmid 4 fault unless mainline's mc_resume programs
+	 * mmUVD_LMI_ADDR_EXT and mmUVD_LMI_EXT40_ADDR with the high bits
+	 * of fw_gpu_addr (it sits in VRAM at 0xF00400000), which redirects
+	 * UVD's MMU to find the firmware via the address-extension path
+	 * instead of needing a vmid 4 PT entry.
 	 *
-	 * Inlined mc_resume minus UDEC:
+	 * Sony's cache offset/size writes below intentionally OVERWRITE
+	 * mc_resume's mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET0/SIZE0 etc — we want Sony's
+	 * Baikal-tested hardcoded values for those, but want mc_resume's
+	 * LMI ADDR_EXT/EXT40 setup as the thing that lets UVD's reads
+	 * actually reach VRAM.
 	 */
-	{
-		uint64_t addr;
-		uint32_t size;
-
-		addr = (adev->uvd.inst->gpu_addr + AMDGPU_UVD_FIRMWARE_OFFSET) >> 3;
-		size = AMDGPU_UVD_FIRMWARE_SIZE(adev) >> 3;
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET0, addr);
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_SIZE0, size);
-
-		addr += size;
-		size = AMDGPU_UVD_HEAP_SIZE >> 3;
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET1, addr);
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_SIZE1, size);
-
-		addr += size;
-		size = (AMDGPU_UVD_STACK_SIZE +
-			(AMDGPU_UVD_SESSION_SIZE * adev->uvd.max_handles)) >> 3;
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET2, addr);
-		WREG32(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_SIZE2, size);
-
-		addr = (adev->uvd.inst->gpu_addr >> 28) & 0xF;
-		WREG32(mmUVD_LMI_ADDR_EXT, (addr << 12) | (addr << 0));
-
-		addr = (adev->uvd.inst->gpu_addr >> 32) & 0xFF;
-		WREG32(mmUVD_LMI_EXT40_ADDR, addr | (0x9 << 16) | (0x1 << 31));
-
-		/* SKIPPED: UDEC_ADDR_CONFIG / _DB / _DBW (would corrupt Liverpool) */
-	}
-
-	/* v76b: still zero LMI_ADDR_EXT/EXT40 to match Sony's post-reset state. */
-	WREG32(mmUVD_LMI_ADDR_EXT, 0);
-	WREG32(mmUVD_LMI_EXT40_ADDR, 0);
+	uvd_v4_2_mc_resume(adev);
 
 	/*
 	 * Cache region descriptors. Sony's Baikal-specific values; the
@@ -829,26 +822,23 @@
 	WREG32(0x1401, RREG32(0x1401) | 8);
 
 	/*
-	 * v76a: LMI_VM_VBASE — Sony's uvd_vcpu_start_baikal reads
-	 * ctx[+0x88] and writes it here, but ctx[+0x88] is never
-	 * initialised on the UVD path (uvd_kmd_hw_init_stage2 sets
-	 * region pointers at +0x50/+0x70/+0x90 but not +0x88; the only
-	 * function that writes +0x88 is uvd_ctx_set_field_88, called
-	 * from uvd_ctx_dma_map_buffer which is only ever called by the
-	 * HDA audio path). So Sony effectively writes VBASE = 0.
+	 * 2026-05-15: LMI_VM_VBASE — write the FIRMWARE GPU address here,
+	 * NOT 0. v76a got this wrong by missing FUN_c88f9010 in Sony's
+	 * source — that function maps Region 1 to UVD-VMID VA 0x300000000
+	 * and stores it in ctx[+0x88]. So Sony writes VBASE = 0x300000000
+	 * (not 0).
 	 *
-	 * v73/v74/v75 wrote fw_gpu_addr here on the assumption that the
-	 * VCPU needed to know where its firmware lives — but the cache
-	 * offset/size writes above (0x3d82..0x3d87) already give the
-	 * VCPU its memory layout. LMI_VM_VBASE appears to be something
-	 * else (a VM base for VCPU's own virtual-address space, possibly
-	 * 0 because the firmware operates on offsets from 0).
+	 * For our Linux port: with patches 0042-0044 mirroring the
+	 * firmware BO at GART VA 0x300000000, fw_gpu_addr equals
+	 * 0x300000000 too. Either way the right thing to write is the
+	 * actual firmware GPU address, NOT zero.
 	 *
-	 * If this is right, the VM fault at page 0x300000 vmid 4 should
-	 * either disappear or move to a different address.
+	 * v73/v74/v75 had this right; v76a regressed it; we restore the
+	 * correct value here. The v76a "VM fault page 0x300000 vmid 4"
+	 * was a SYMPTOM of writing 0 (UVD then read from page 0).
 	 */
-	WREG32(0x3c69, 0);    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_LO = ctx[+0x88]_lo (= 0) */
-	WREG32(0x3c68, 0);    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_HI = ctx[+0x88]_hi (= 0) */
+	WREG32(0x3c69, lower_32_bits(fw_gpu_addr));    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_LO */
+	WREG32(0x3c68, upper_32_bits(fw_gpu_addr));    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_HI */
 
 	/* Clear DMA + soft-reset bit 0 — first stage of VCPU release. */
 	WREG32(0x3da5, 0);
